# This is the gaussian model in which we will train our initial points
def train_gaussian_process(x_train,y_train):
    kernel = RBF()
    gpr = GaussianProcessRegressor(kernel=kernel, n_restarts_optimizer = 4, normalize_y = False)
    gpr.fit(x_train,y_train)
    return gpr

  • Sample a further EIGHT points using the Expected Improvement acquisition function.
  • At each iteration, print the value of x selected by the Expected Improvement acquisition function for evaluation, and the value of function evaluated at x.
  • After all iterations are complete, print the best (i.e. lowest) point found (both x and the function value at x).
In [1]:
# Now implement the initial_sample function in the Bayesian optimization loop

def initial_sample(n_init,x_low,x_high):
    x_0 = random.uniform(x_low,x_high)
    y_0 = Problem21(x_0)
    x_train = np.array([[x_0]])
    y_train = np.array([[y_0]])
    i = 1
    while i < n_init:
        x_i = random.uniform(x_low,x_high)
        y_i = Problem21(x_i)
        x_train = np.vstack((x_train,x_i))
        y_train = np.vstack((y_train,y_i))
        i = i+1
    return x_train, y_train

In [11]:
# This is the first function of baysian optimization
def expected_improvement(x,y_pred,std_dev,f_min):
    arg = f_min - y_pred
    EI_exploit = arg*norm.cdf(arg/std_dev)
    EI_explor = std_dev*norm.pdf(arg/std_dev)
    EI = EI_explor + EI_exploit
    return EI

# This is the second function which will help us find the best coordinates that will fit in the function
def maximize_acquisition_function(gpr,x_train,y_train,f_min,x_low,x_high):
    n_grid_points = 2000
    x_grid = np.linspace(x_low,x_high,n_grid_points)
    
    EI_max = -1
    x_next = x_grid[0]
    
    for x_val in x_grid:
        y_pred, y_std = gpr.predict(x_val.reshape(-1, 1), return_std=True, return_cov=False)
        EI_val = expected_improvement(x,y_pred[0][0],y_std[0],f_min)
    
    if EI_val > EI_max:
        EI_max = EI_val
        x_next = x_val
    return x_next
In [14]:
# This is the final function which iterates and tries to find the best value of x and y
def evaluate_x_next(x_next):
    y_next = Problem21(x_next)
    return y_next
In [15]:
# Bayesian optimization loop
iter_max = 20
iteration = 0

#x_train, y_train = initial_sample(n_init,x_low,x_high)
x_best = float(min(x_train))
y_best = float(min(y_train))

while iteration < iter_max:
    gp = train_gaussian_process(x_train,y_train)
    
    x_next = maximize_acquisition_function(gp,x_train,y_train,y_best,x_low,x_high)
    y_next = evaluate_x_next(x_next)

    if y_next < y_best:
            y_best = y_next
            x_best = x_next
        
    x_train = np.vstack((x_train,x_next))
    y_train = np.vstack((y_train,y_next))
    iteration = iteration + 1
    print(iteration,x_next,y_next)
    
print("Best point found: ",x_best,y_best)

Part 2 Supervised Learning¶

The dataset that we will use for this task will be provided and you can downland it from the Blackboard. The dataset includes three files for three exercises. The 1st, 5th and 9th columns (with long data like 2107727051) are time stamps when the data were collected, while other columns contain readings from different sensors. The classification problem is to predict the type of exercise. In this task, you are required to use k fold cross-validation.

1. [Pre-processing]¶

In this step, you will be focussing on preparing the datasets, i.e. loading, exploring the datasets, displaying, reorganising data, removing noise and normalisation etc. [3 marks]

Dealing with outliers using IQR method¶

In this method we calculate the lower and upper quartiles and then calculate the interquartile range. All the values that do no lie in the range are omitted. We did this as per need on all the features in the given dataset.

In [39]:
final_df['Sensor 1'].plot.density(color='blue')
plt.title('Density plot for Sensor 1')
plt.show()
In [40]:
q3, q1 = np.percentile(final_df['Sensor 1'], [75 ,25])
iqr = q3-q1
 = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
 = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
final_df = final_df[(final_df['Sensor 1'] >= LB) & (final_df['Sensor 1'] <= UB)]

4. [Summary and Discussion]¶

Summarise your findings, discuss the factors that could have impacts on your results and propose potential improvement. [2 marks]

Summary and Discussion:¶

In this task we were asked to apply two classification models i.e KNN and SVM.

Task1: Data Preprocessing: We first imported the dataset using pandas library. We then created a label column to label each excercise. After creating the label the data was then merged into a single dataframe. We then checked for any missing or duplicate values and also dealt with any potential noise in the dataset using IQR method. We also renamed the columns to make the columns more meaningful.

Task2: Feature Extraction: In this task we first created a heatmap to see the relationship of all the variables with our labelled data. Since we saw no significant relationship thats why we decided to choose all variables as our predictors and label variable as our target. We then split the dataset into test and train in the ratio 70:30

Task3: Classification: In this section we first applied KNN classification model. We created a pipeline which scaled the values in the KNN model. We the used GridSearchCV to find the best parameters for the model by testing the model on K values from 1 to 30 and choosing the optimal value of K. After that we created the confusion matrix and classification report to see the performance of our model. Based on the results we can see that the KNN model performed really well as we acheived an accuracy of 96% in successfully labelleing the data.

We then applied SVM and applied similar steps to what we did in KNN. Here we again acheived a good performance as SVM also managed to accurately predict 96% of the data correctly.

Suggested Improvements: The results can be further improved by removing variables with very low correlation with the label dataset such as sensor 6 and rerunning the classification models to see any improvements.

Tune the parameter setting, select the optimal cluster number using the elbow method¶
In [77]:
# We have standardized/normalized the values of each feature in X variable
scaled_X = scaler.fit_transform(X)
In [78]:
# This function helps us find the best value of K
ssd = []

for k in range(2,30):
    
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    
    
    model.fit(scaled_X)
    
    #Sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center.
    ssd.append(model.inertia_)
In [79]:
# Visualizing the function above showing us the best value of k. This called the elbow method.
# Here we choose the value where we see the bending of the curve which is around 6. This is just an estimate.
# We can change the value of K to see if the performance improves.
plt.plot(range(2,30),ssd,'o--')
plt.xlabel("K Value")
plt.ylabel(" Sum of Squared Distances")

Use clustering validity indices to confirm the selection of K value¶

This is basically validation of the clusters created.

In [81]:

1.5478948504906136

The silhouette score falls within the range [-1, 1]. The silhouette score of 1 means that the clusters are very dense and nicely separated. The score of 0 means that clusters are overlapping. The score of less than 0 means that data belonging to clusters may be wrong/incorrect.

In [82]:

silhouette_avg

[0.19041008 0.12971047 0.06462781 ... 0.06607044 0.0594976  0.08563459]

The index is the ratio of the sum of between-clusters dispersion and of within-cluster dispersion for all clusters (where dispersion is defined as the sum of distances squared). The score is higher when clusters are dense and well separated.

4. [Evaluation]¶

Evaluate the performance of these two clustering methods by comparing the clustering results with the known exercise type information.

The two clustering method implemented are Kmeans and Hierarchial. We first applied K means cluster. We determined the number of clusters using the elbow method. Based on the diagram we determined that we should create atleast 6 clusters. After creating the clusters we evaluated the clusters using 3 method, davies_bouldin, silhouette and calinski_harabasz_scores. Based on the results we saw that we did not acheive an ideal cluster. better clusters could have been obtained if we had done PCA first and then applied the clusters. The next cluster algorithm applied is Hierarchial cluster. We again visualised the model using a dendogram and then evaluated the performance of the model using the same metrics. Based on the metrics we saw that hierchial clustering did a worse job than kmeans cluster.
